		<li class="alt" id="comment-37591">
						<div class="commentbyline">lotuseater writes:</div>
						
                        <div class="commenttext"><p>For the past 6 years I have worked in aspirational retail, aka fine wine. Most definitely the rich are being subsidized by the young, poor, badly organized and socially mal-adjusted. This is proven by how credit and debit cards are processed. At a minimum a retailer must account for the average processing charge administered by a few giant payment networks. Online is controlled by Authorize.net and the world of swiped cards is dominated by Chase Paymentech and Wells Fargo. These networks (with ineffectual federal regulation) charge a dizzying number of &#8216;rates&#8217; dependent on the type of card used, and to a much lesser extent the amount of the transaction. So, a Visa Signature Business Card takes a higher percentage of a sale than a standard Visa credit card or Visa debit card (ok, I&#8217;m over simplifying but there are more than 50 different &#8216;rates&#8217;). The better your credit, the more rewards your card gives you. The worse your credit, the less rewards your card gives you.  All those miles or 1.5% cash rebates Alec Baldwin and Samuel Jackson promise you on TV are being paid for by the poor. So much for Hollywood progressives.</p>
</div>

