		<li class="alt" id="comment-37623">
						<div class="commentbyline"><a href='http://Thorntonhalldesign.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Thornton Hall</a> writes:</div>
						
                        <div class="commenttext"><p>Fresh from reading an article in HBR from June 2013 called &#8220;Transient Advantage&#8221; by Columbia Prof Rita Gunther McGrath. I wonder if her business school thinking has insights for Econ, I came back to this post. </p>
<p>She argues that &#8220;moats&#8221; are a thing of the past in most industries, like you do. She suggests that the answer is a series of transient advantages that are short lived but profitable instead of one big moat. The hurdle is basically two fold: the inertia of large successful enterprises and the fact that the creative people who develop new advantages are not the same set of people who run &#8220;mature&#8221; companies. </p>
<p>Is there a dynamic where the less creative people see rent seeking as the only option for continued profits where a more nimble organization which hasn&#8217;t alienated all the start-up/ramp-up employees is able to see and develop other more productive advantages?</p>
